{{Infobox Officeholder |name = Elena Salgado Méndez |image = Elena Salgado en rueda de prensa.jpg |office = [[First Vice President (Spain)|First Deputy Prime Minister of Spain]] |term_start = 11 July 2011 |term_end = 21 December 2011 |primeminister = [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]] |primeminister2 = [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]] |primeminister3 = [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]] |primeminister4 = [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]] |primeminister5 = [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]] |predecessor = [[Alfredo Pérez Rubalcaba]] |successor = [[Soraya Sáenz de Santamaría]] |office2 = [[Second Vice President (Spain)|Second Deputy Prime Minister of Spain]] |term_start2 = 7 April 2009 |term_end2 = 11 July 2011 |predecessor2 = [[Pedro Solbes]] |successor2 = [[Manuel Chaves]] |office3 = [[Minister of Economy and Finance (Spain)|Minister of Economy and Finance]] |term_start3 = 7 April 2009 |term_end3 = 21 December 2011 |predecessor3 = [[Pedro Solbes]] |successor3 = [[Luis de Guindos]] <small>(As Minister of Economy and Competitiveness)</small></br>[[Cristóbal Montoro Romero|Cristóbal Montoro]] <small>(As Minister of Finance and Public Administrations)</small> |office4 = [[Cabinet of Spain|Minister for Public Administration]] |term_start4 = 9 July 2007 |term_end4 = 7 April 2009 |predecessor4 = [[Jordi Sevilla]] |successor4 = [[Manuel Chaves]] <small>(As Minister of Territorial Policy)</small> |office5 = [[Cabinet of Spain|Minister of Health]] |term_start5 = 18 April 2004 |term_end5 = 9 July 2007 |predecessor5 = [[Ana Pastor]] |successor5 = [[Bernat Soria]] |birth_date = {{bda|1949|5|12|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Ourense]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] |death_date = |death_place = |party = [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|Socialist Workers' Party]] |alma_mater = [[Technical University of Madrid]], [[Complutense University of Madrid]] |profession = [[Industrial Engineer]], [[Economist]] |religion = [[Roman Catholic]] }} '''Elena Salgado Méndez''' ({{IPA-es|eˈlena salˈɣaðo ˈmendeθ}}) (b. 12 May 1949 in [[Ourense]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], [[Spain]]) is a [[Spain|Spanish]] politician who served as the [[Minister of Economy and Finance (Spain)|Minister of Economy and Finance]] and [[First Vice President (Spain)|First Vice President]] (i.e. [[deputy prime minister]]) of Spain, in the Socialist Party government of [[José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero]]. She succeeded [[Pedro Solbes]] as Finance Minister in April 2009 in a surprise move,<ref>[http://www.economist.com/world/europe/displaystory.cfm?story_id=13447367 The Economist 8 April 2009 accessed 10 April 2009]</ref> and held the office until the fall of the Zapatero Administration at the 2011 parliamentary elections.
A graduate of Industrial Engineering and Economic Science,<ref>[http://www.elpais.com/todo-sobre/persona/Elena/Salgado/5694/ Biography at El Pais, accessed 10 April 2009]</ref> she had previously been Health Minister (2004-2007) and Minister for Public Administration (2007-2009). Despite her [[Galician people|Galician origin]] she has been a deputy for [[Cantabria (Spanish Congress Electoral District)|Cantabria province]] since the 2008 election.<ref>[http://www.congreso.es/portal/page/portal/Congreso/Congreso/Diputados/BusqForm?_piref73_1333155_73_1333154_1333154.next_page=/wc/fichaDiputado&idDiputado=81&idLegislatura=9 Biography at Spanish Congress site, accessed 10 April 2009]</ref>
